NOT commission them something bright and pastel to be 'funny', as a 'challenge', or because you want it in 'their style' . If they are not creating that content and do not specify they will do it, THEY PROBABLY WON'T. If anything, ASK BEFORE YOU PAY.

( The above has happened to me far too many times. )

❀ DO be clear about the style the artist has as well as anatomy, coloring, eyes, etc.

❀ DON'T commission someone something they've obviously not drawn or have any interest in drawing. If the artist draws dark and edgy, DO

❀ DO treat artists as you'd treat a professional coworker

❀ DO NOT SEXUALLY HARRASS, HAZE, ETC. AN ARTIST. ARTISTS ARE NOT HERE TO FULFILL YOUR FANTASIES. ARTISTS DO NOT WANT TO PARTICIPATE IN YOUR FETISH. DO NOT HOLD TIPS OVER THEM FOR ENGAGING YOU.

❀ DO remember artists work on their own art at their own preferred time, pace, etc.

❀ DON'T assume an art is forgetting / ignoring / dislikes you because they're posting other things. It is their right as an independent human being to enjoy making art for themselves too.

❀ DO remember your artist is someone with a life, family, and mental wellness outside your own.

❀ DON'T think that an artist is ignoring your commission because they don't like you. This is stressful and can result in a longer delay or refund.

❀ DO UNDERSTAND ARTISTS USE THEIR OWN PALETTES.

❀ DON'T be upset an artist didn't use the exact palette you provide. It doesn't always work with the style, and sometimes ppl just don't like working w xyz shade.

❀ DO understand that your commission will not be perfect, and like all art, will have imperfections.

❀ DO NOT use dissatisfaction with a commission as a point of a refund or public callout UNLESS IT IS NOTABLY BAD. A few minor details missing isn't the end of the world.

❀ DO understand that art is hard, and the will and drive to work on art varies from artist to artist.

❀ DON'T rush or try to give a 'talking to' to an artist who has been late on your commission IF THEY HAVE KEPT CONTACT. They obviously care and aren't trying to take ur money.

❀ DO be clear about any deadlines, gift commissions, holiday commissions, etc.

❀ DON'T alert of these last minute, or expect your commission to be done by a promised date unless specifically told otherwise.

❀ DO keep in contact with someone you have requested a commission from.

❀ DON'T ghost, lose contact, etc. This applies to if you can't afford a commission, or if you got one. If you can't afford it, tell us. If you disappear, we won't always try to find you.

❀ DO use references when contacting an artist about poses, colors, themes, etc.

❀ DON'T use other art as reference points. Not all artists are comfortable with it. DON'T use others OCs as custom references.

❀ DO treat artists with professionalism.

❀ DON'T treat artists as your friend. Don't send memes, don't keysmash, don't talk abt your daily life - a lot of artists want to finish the commission and be done. If they talk to you first in a friendly way, you can in return!

( The above applies to Ko-Fi commissions.)

❀ DO be clear with your commission request, and get as much information as you can in the first message.

❀ DON'T be vague and unclear, and then upset with what you get. This is frustrating for both parties involved.

❀ DO leave contact information in commission requests, whether that be an email, Twitter @, or anything of the sort.

❀ DON'T expect us to hunt you down. Some artists will simply not touch the commission until contacted, others won't put in the effort. They don't owe it to you.

❀ DO have a clear, concise reference an artist can both understand and colorpick from.

❀ DON'T use repeating watermarks, large watermarks, or watermarks that cover more than 50% of the drawing. Artists COLORPICK. We are not looking to take your OC, we want to finish the art.

↳ THE DO's and DON'Ts of Commissioning

And honestly, I'm a full advocate for not allowing unmonitored internet access until they're older. I don't think someone needs to be 12-13-14 in fandoms with those who are decades older than them - because that's unavoidable.

It's the job of those around the child, who has access to the internet, to guide them *into* learning safety. You don't sit a kid in front of a laptop and expect them to learn. My parents thought they could, and I learned the hard way.

I wish people would realize that it isn't a child's job to keep themselves safe online too. I thought it was mine too. But families, schools, elder siblings, etc. need to have talks with their younger siblings *about* the dangers of predators on the internet.
